"Nielsen L., Clemmensen L.B.","Sea-level markers identified in ground-penetrating radar data collected across a modern beach ridge system in a microtidal regime",2009,"Terra Nova","21","6",,"474","479",,,10.1111/j.1365-3121.2009.00904.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-71049143176&partnerID=40&md5=021072104957d946a8d9acf3d3bbd353","Department of Geography and Geology, University of Copenhagen, Øster Voldgade 10, DK-1350 Copenhagen K, Denmark","Nielsen, L., Department of Geography and Geology, University of Copenhagen, Øster Voldgade 10, DK-1350 Copenhagen K, Denmark; Clemmensen, L.B., Department of Geography and Geology, University of Copenhagen, Øster Voldgade 10, DK-1350 Copenhagen K, Denmark","Sea-level rise has been related to global warming. The modern system on the northern coast of Anholt, Denmark, may well be analogous to other beach ridge systems formed in microtidal regimes and our results should have impact on estimation of past sea-level variation. Ground-penetrating radar data collected across the modern (<30 years old) berm, beach ridge and swale deposits resolve downlapping reflections interpreted to mark sea level at the time of deposition. Existing time series of sea-level data constrain actual sea-level variation. Nineteen readings of sea-level markers made along our profile fluctuate within -0.42 and 0.57 m above present mean sea level, consistent with 95% of the sea-level data. These fluctuations reflect tidal effects and meteorological conditions. Main data uncertainties are well-known and the sea-level markers may be identified with a high degree of confidence. © 2009 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.",,"beach ridge; berm; coastal zone; confidence interval; deposition; estimation method; global warming; ground penetrating radar; marine sediment; sea level change; time series; Anholt; Denmark; Eurasia; Europe; Midtjylland; Northern Europe; Scandinavia",,,,,,"Bjørnsen, M., Clemmensen, L.B., Murray, A., Pedersen, K., New evidence of the Littorina transgressions in the Kattegat: optically stimulated luminescence dating of a beach ridge system on Anholt, Denmark (2008) Boreas, 37, pp. 157-168; Bristow, C.S., Pucillo, K., Quatifying rates of coastal progadation from sediment volume using GPR and OSL: the Holocene fill of the Guichen Bay, south-east South Austalia (2006) Sedimentology, 53, pp. 769-788; Clemmensen, L.B., Andreasen, F., Heinemeier, J., Murray, A., A Holocene coastal aeolian system, Vejers, Denmark: landscape evolution and sequence stratigraphy (2001) Terra Nova, 13, pp. 129-134; Engels, S., Roberts, M.C., The architecture of prograding sandy-gravel beach ridges formed during the last Holocene highstand: Southwestern British Columbia, Canada (2005) J. Sed. Res., 75, pp. 1052-1064; Fraser, C., Hill, P.R., Allard, M., Morphology and facies architecture of a falling sea level strandplain, Umiujaq, Hudson Bay, Canada (2005) Sedimentology, 52, pp. 141-160; Goy, J.L., Zazo, C., Dabrio, C.J., A beach-ridge progradation complex reflecting periodical sea-level and climate variability during the Holocene (Gulf of Almería, western Mediterranean) (2003) Geomorphology, 50, pp. 251-268; Gregersen, S., Leth, J., Lind, G., Lykke-Andersen, H., Earthquake activity and its relationship with geologically recent motion in Denmark (1996) Tectonophysics, 257, pp. 265-273; van Heteren, S., Fitzgerald, D.M., McKinlay, P.A., Buynevich, I.V., Radar facies of paraglacial barrier systems: coastal New England, USA (1998) Sedimentology, 45, pp. 181-200; van Heteren, S., Huntley, D.J., van de Plassche, O., Lubberts, R.K., Optical dating of dune sand for the study of sea-level change (2000) Geology, 28, pp. 411-414; Jensen, J.B., Petersen, K.S., Konradi, P., Kuijpers, A., Bennike, O., Lemke, W., Endler, R., Neotectonic, sea-level changes and biological evolution in the Fennoscandian Border Zone of the southern Kattegat (2002) Boreas, 31, pp. 133-150; Johnston, J.W., Thompson, T.A., Baedke, S.J., Baker, G.S., Jol, H.M., 